# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atac-seq
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] ATAC-seq identifies accessible DNA regions by probing open chromatin with hyperactive mutant Tn5 Transposase that inserts sequencing adapters into open regions of the genome.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] While naturally occurring transposases have a low level of activity, ATAC-seq employs the mutated hyperactive transposase.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] In a process called "tagmentation", Tn5 transposase cleaves and tags double-stranded DNA with sequencing adaptors in a single enzymatic step.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] The tagged DNA fragments are then purified, PCR-amplified, and sequenced using next-generation sequencing.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Sequencing reads can then be used to infer regions of increased accessibility as well as to map regions of transcription factor binding sites and nucleosome positions.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] The number of reads for a region correlate with how open that chromatin is, at single nucleotide resolution.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] ATAC-seq requires no sonication or phenol-chloroform extraction like FAIRE-seq; no antibodies like ChIP-seq; and no sensitive enzymatic digestion like MNase-seq or DNase-seq.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] ATAC-seq preparation can be completed in under three hours.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] ATAC-Seq analysis is used to investigate a number of chromatin-accessibility signatures.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] The most common use is nucleosome mapping experiments, but it can be applied to mapping transcription factor binding sites, adapted to map DNA methylation sites, or combined with sequencing techniques.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] The utility of high-resolution enhancer mapping ranges from studying the evolutionary divergence of enhancer usage (e.g. between chimps and humans) during development and uncovering a lineage-specific enhancer map used during blood cell differentiation.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] ATAC-Seq has also been applied to defining the genome-wide chromatin accessibility landscape in human cancers, and revealing an overall decrease in chromatin accessibility in macular degeneration.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Computational footprinting methods can be performed on ATAC-seq to find cell specific binding sites and transcription factors with cell specific activity.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] ATAC-seq has found increasing applications in clinical research and disease studies.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] EPIC-ATAC has been developed as a deconvolution framework to quantify cell-type heterogeneity in bulk tumor ATAC-seq data, enabling analysis of regulatory processes underlying tumor development and correlation with clinical variables in cancer research.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] In immunology, ATAC-seq has been used to characterize dynamic epigenetic changes in T cell exhaustion, revealing that exhausted T cells possess unique chromatin accessibility patterns compared to naive, effector, and memory T cells, with implications for cancer immunotherapy.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] The Cancer Genome Atlas has generated genome-wide chromatin accessibility profiles of 410 tumor samples spanning 23 cancer types, identifying 562,709 transposase-accessible DNA elements and revealing genetic risk loci of cancer predisposition as active DNA regulatory elements.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Integrative analysis combining ATAC-seq with RNA-seq has been used to identify novel oncogenes and elucidate regulatory mechanisms in hepatocellular carcinoma.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Modifications to the ATAC-seq protocol have been made to accommodate single-cell analysis.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Microfluidics can be used to separate single nuclei and perform ATAC-seq reactions individually.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] With this approach, single cells are captured by either a microfluidic device or a liquid deposition system before tagmentation.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] An alternative technique that does not require single cell isolation is combinatorial cellular indexing.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] This technique uses barcoding to measure chromatin accessibility in thousands of individual cells; it can generate epigenomic profiles from 10,000-100,000 cells per experiment.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] But combinatorial cellular indexing requires additional, custom-engineered equipment or a large quantity of custom, modified Tn5.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Recently, a pooled barcode method called sci-CAR was developed, allowing joint profiling of chromatin accessibility and gene expression of single cells.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Computational analysis of scATAC-seq is based on construction of a count matrix with number of reads per open chromatin regions.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Open chromatin regions can be defined, for example, by standard peak calling of pseudo bulk ATAC-seq data.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Further steps include data reduction with PCA and clustering of cells. scATAC-seq matrices can be extremely large (hundreds of thousands of regions) and is extremely sparse, i.e. less than 3% of entries are non-zero.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Therefore, imputation of count matrix is another crucial step performed by using various methods such as non-negative matrix factorization.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] As with bulk ATAC-seq, scATAC-seq allows finding regulators like transcription factors controlling gene expression of cells.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] This can be achieved by looking at the number of reads around TF motifs or footprinting analysis.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Spatial ATAC-seq combines chromatin accessibility profiling with spatial information, enabling researchers to map epigenetic landscapes while preserving tissue architecture.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] This method combines in situ Tn5 transposition chemistry with microfluidic deterministic barcoding to perform spatially resolved chromatin accessibility analysis on tissue sections at the cellular level and genome scale.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] The technique has been applied to co-profiling of the epigenome and transcriptome, facilitating investigation of the correlation between accessible peaks and expressed genes pixel by pixel in the tissue context.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] A commercially implemented form of deterministic barcoding for spatial ATAC-seq is provided by AtlasXomics, which commercializes the DBiT-seq microfluidic barcoding technology originally developed in the Fan laboratory.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] The platform generates ~10 μm spatial pixels through orthogonal microfluidic barcoding flows and is compatible with both fresh-frozen and FFPE (formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded) tissue sections.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Peer-reviewed applications of AtlasXomics-based spatial ATAC-seq include mapping the chromatin accessibility landscape of the human dorsal root ganglion using combined spatial ATAC-seq and CUT&Tag.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Additional studies using this platform have been reported in preprint form, extending spatial epigenomic analysis to cancer models, developmental tissues, and immune microenvironments.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Recent advances have enabled simultaneous profiling of chromatin accessibility alongside other molecular modalities in the same cells or tissue sections.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Spatial ATAC–RNA-seq and spatial CUT&Tag–RNA-seq allow co-profiling of genome-wide chromatin accessibility or histone modifications in conjunction with whole transcriptome on the same tissue section at near-single-cell resolution.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] ATAC-seq data analysis presents unique methodological challenges due to data sparsity and the need for specialized bioinformatics tools.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] The major steps include pre-analysis (quality check and alignment), core analysis (peak calling), and advanced analysis (peak differential analysis and annotation, motif enrichment, footprinting, and nucleosome position analysis).
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] MACS2 (Model-based Analysis of ChIP-seq 2) remains the most widely used peak caller for ATAC-seq data analysis, serving as the default peak caller in the ENCODE ATAC-seq pipeline.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Originally developed for ChIP-seq, MACS2 has been adapted for ATAC-seq analysis and performs well for identifying regions of enriched transposase accessibility, though it requires parameter optimization for ATAC-seq-specific characteristics.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] Standardized analysis workflows have been developed, including the nf-core/atacseq pipeline, which provides a comprehensive, reproducible framework for ATAC-seq data processing from raw reads to final peak calls and quality control metrics.
[src:atac-seq/atac-seq] This Nextflow-based pipeline incorporates best practices for adapter trimming, alignment, duplicate removal, peak calling, and downstream analysis, facilitating standardized processing across different research groups and computational environments.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Eukaryotic chromatin consists primarily of DNA associated with histone proteins and numerous other chromatin-binding factors that contribute to genome organization and regulation.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chromatin packages long DNA molecules into compact structures while controlling access to genetic information for processes such as transcription, DNA replication, and DNA repair.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] During cell division, chromatin facilitates proper segregation of chromosomes in anaphase; the characteristic shapes of chromosomes visible during this stage are the result of DNA being coiled into highly condensed chromatin.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chromatin organization is often described at several structural levels.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] At the most basic level, DNA wrapped around histone octamers forms nucleosomes connected by stretches of linker DNA, producing a structure sometimes referred to as a “beads-on-a-string” fiber approximately 10–11 nm in diameter.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Nucleosome arrays can interact with each other and with linker histones to form higher-order chromatin structures.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] 30-nm chromatin fiber has been observed *in vitro*, although its presence and prevalence in living cells remain debated.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] At larger genomic scales, chromatin is organized into loops and domains that contribute to the three-dimensional architecture of the genome.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chromosomes are further partitioned into compartments associated with active (euchromatin) or inactive (heterochromatin) chromatin states, and individual chromosomes occupy distinct spatial regions within the nucleus known as chromosome territories.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Many organisms exhibit variations in chromatin organization.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] For example, spermatozoa and avian red blood cells have more tightly packed chromatin than most eukaryotic cells.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] In contrast, some protozoa such as trypanosomatid do not DNA condense their chromatin into visible chromosomes at all.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Bacteria organize their DNA differently, forming a chromatin or nucleoid structure organized by nucleoid-associated proteins including H-NS and StpA.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Some archaeal species encode histone proteins, and package DNA into nucleosome-like assemblies of variable size, sometimes referred to as hypernucleosomes.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chromatin organization also varies throughout the cell cycle.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] During interphase, chromatin is generally less condensed, allowing access to RNA and DNA polymerases that transcribe and replicate the DNA.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The local structure of chromatin during interphase depends on the specific genes present in the DNA.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] During mitosis and meiosis, chromatin becomes highly compacted to facilitate the segregation of chromosomes.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Within interphase nuclei, genomic regions differ in their degree of compaction and transcriptional activity.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Actively transcribed regions are often associated with less condensed chromatin known as euchromatin, whereas transcriptionally inactive or repressed regions are frequently enriched in more compact heterochromatin.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chemical modifications of chromatin components, often so-called epigenetic modification, including histone tails methylation and acetylation also alters local chromatin structure and therefore gene expression.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The primary protein components of chromatin are histones.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Nucleosome, the fundamental basic unit of chromatin, consists of DNA wrapped around a histone octamer containing two copies each of the core histones Histone H2A, Histone H2B, Histone H3, and Histone H4.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Approximately 147 base pairs of DNA wrap around this histone octamer to form the nucleosome core particle.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Neighboring nucleosomes are connected by stretches of linker DNA, which vary in length among organisms and cell types but typically range from about 20 to 60 base pairs.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Arrays of nucleosomes connected by linker DNA form an extended fiber often described as a “beads-on-a-string” structure approximately 10–11 nm in diameter under low-salt or experimentally reconstituted conditions.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] In addition to core histones, a linker histone H1 binds near the entry and exit sites of DNA on the nucleosome and contributes to higher-order chromatin organization.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The nucleosome core particle, together with histone H1, is known as a chromatosome.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The nucleosomes bind DNA non-specifically, as required by their function in general DNA packaging.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] There are, however, large DNA sequence preferences that govern nucleosome positioning.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] This is due primarily to the varying physical properties of different DNA sequences: For instance, adenine (A), and thymine (T) is more favorably compressed into the inner minor grooves.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] This means nucleosomes can bind preferentially at one position approximately every 10 base pairs (the helical repeat of DNA)- where the DNA is rotated to maximize the number of A and T bases that will lie in the inner minor groove (see nucleic acid structure).
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Under certain experimental conditions, nucleosome arrays can fold into more compact structures with diameters of approximately 30 nm.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Early models proposed that chromatin fibers adopt regular helical arrangements, including a one-start solenoid model and a two-start zigzag model.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] However, the existence of a uniform 30-nm chromatin fiber in living cells remains debated.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Studies using cryo-electron microscopy and other high-resolution imaging methods have suggested that chromatin in many cell types forms irregular and dynamic nucleosome assemblies rather than regular 30-nm fibers.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The beads-on-a-string chromatin structure has a tendency to form loops.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] These loops allow interactions between different regions of DNA by bringing them closer to each other, which increases the efficiency of gene interactions.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] This process is dynamic, with loops forming and disappearing.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] For example, Jpx regulates the binding sites of CTCF molecules along the DNA fiber.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chromatin compartments are large-scale structural domains of the genome that reflect the segregation of chromatin with similar transcriptional and epigenetic properties.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Genome-wide chromosome conformation capture experiments have revealed that chromosomes are partitioned into at least two major compartment types, commonly referred to as A and B compartments.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] A compartments are generally enriched in transcriptionally active chromatin, open chromatin marks, and gene-rich regions, whereas B compartments are associated with transcriptionally inactive chromatin, heterochromatin, and interactions with nuclear structures such as the nuclear lamina.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] These compartments represent preferential long-range interactions between genomic regions with similar chromatin states and contribute to the spatial organization of chromosomes within the nucleus.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chromatin structure is highly dynamic and changes throughout the cell cycle and in response to cellular signals.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Histone proteins play a central role in organizing chromatin and can undergo a wide range of post-translational modifications, including acetylation, methylation, phosphorylation, and ubiquitination (see histone modification).
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] These modifications occur primarily on the flexible N-terminal tails of histones that extend outward from the nucleosome core.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The positively charged histone cores only partially counteract the negative charge of the DNA phosphate backbone resulting in a negative net charge of the overall structure.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] An imbalance of charge within the polymer causes electrostatic repulsion between neighboring chromatin regions that promote interactions with positively charged proteins, molecules, and cations.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] As these modifications occur, the electrostatic environment surrounding the chromatin will flux and the level of chromatin compaction will alter.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The consequences in terms of chromatin accessibility and compaction depend both on the modified amino acid and the type of modification.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Different histone modifications are associated with distinct chromatin states.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Multiple histone modifications can occur simultaneously on the same nucleosome, creating combinations of regulatory signals sometimes referred to as the *histone code*.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] For example, developmental genes in mammalian embryonic stem cells often carry both activating (H3K4me3) and repressive (H3K27me3) marks in a configuration known as bivalent structure, which is involved into cell fate transtition during early mammalian development.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Polycomb-group proteins play a role in regulating genes through modulation of chromatin structure.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Enzymes that add, remove, or recognize histone modifications are often described as chromatin writers, erasers, and readers, respectively.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] For additional information, see Chromatin variant, Histone modifications in chromatin regulation and RNA polymerase control by chromatin structure.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chromatin and its interaction with enzymes has been researched, and a conclusion being made is that it is relevant and an important factor in gene expression.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Allfrey, a professor at Rockefeller University, stated that RNA synthesis is related to histone acetylation.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The lysine amino acid attached to the end of the histones is positively charged.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The acetylation of these tails would make the chromatin ends neutral, allowing for DNA access.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] When the chromatin decondenses, the DNA is open to entry of molecular machinery.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Fluctuations between open and closed chromatin may contribute to the discontinuity of transcription, or transcriptional bursting.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Other factors are probably involved, such as the association and dissociation of transcription factor complexes with chromatin.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Specifically, RNA polymerase and transcriptional proteins have been shown to congregate into droplets via phase separation, and recent studies have suggested that 10 nm chromatin demonstrates liquid-like behavior increasing the targetability of genomic DNA.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The interactions between linker histones and disordered tail regions act as an electrostatic glue organizing large-scale chromatin into a dynamic, liquid-like domain.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Decreased chromatin compaction comes with increased chromatin mobility and easier transcriptional access to DNA.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The phenomenon, as opposed to simple probabilistic models of transcription, can account for the high variability in gene expression occurring between cells in isogenic populations.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] DNA can adopt several conformations, most commonly referred to as A-, B-, and Z-DNA.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] B-DNA is the predominant form found under physiological conditions and is the canonical right-handed double helix described by Watson and Crick.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] A-DNA is also a right-handed helix but is more compact and is typically observed under dehydrating conditions or in certain DNA–RNA hybrid structures.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Z-DNA differs from these forms in that it is a left-handed helix with a zigzag backbone.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Transitions between B-DNA and Z-DNA can occur in regions experiencing high torsional stress, such as those generated during transcription.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Because of these properties, Z-DNA has been proposed to play roles in chromatin organization and gene regulation.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Local DNA sequence composition and structural flexibility influence how DNA interacts with histone proteins and other chromatin-associated factors.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] For example, sequences enriched in adenine and thymine can bend more easily, affecting nucleosome positioning along the genome.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The spatial arrangement of the chromatin within the nucleus is not random - specific regions of the chromatin can be found in certain territories.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Territories are, for example, the lamina-associated domains (LADs), and the topologically associating domains (TADs), which are bound together by protein complexes.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Polymer physics approaches have been widely used to model chromatin folding and genome organization.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] In particular, mechanisms such as loop extrusion, mediated by protein complexes including cohesin, have been proposed to explain the formation of chromatin loops and domain boundaries observed in chromosome conformation capture experiments.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] **Metaphase**: The metaphase structure of chromatin differs vastly to that of interphase.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] It is optimised for physical strength and manageability, forming the classic chromosome structure seen in karyotypes.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The structure of the condensed chromatin is thought to be loops of 30 nm fibre to a central scaffold of proteins.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] **Chromosome scaffolds** play an important role to hold the chromatin into compact chromosomes.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Loops of 30 nm structure further condense with scaffold, into higher order structures.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chromosome scaffolds are made of proteins including condensin, type IIA topoisomerase and kinesin family member 4 (KIF4).
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The physical strength of chromatin is vital for this stage of division to prevent shear damage to the DNA as the daughter chromosomes are separated.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] To maximise strength the composition of the chromatin changes as it approaches the centromere, primarily through alternative histone H1 analogues.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] During mitosis, although most of the chromatin is tightly compacted, there are small regions that are not as tightly compacted.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] These regions often correspond to promoter regions of genes that were active in that cell type prior to chromatin formation.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The lack of compaction of these regions is called bookmarking, which is an epigenetic mechanism believed to be important for transmitting to daughter cells the "memory" of which genes were active prior to entry into mitosis.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] This bookmarking mechanism is needed to help transmit this memory because transcription ceases during mitosis.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] During metazoan spermiogenesis, the spermatid's chromatin is remodeled into a more spaced-packaged, widened, almost crystal-like structure.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] This process is associated with the cessation of transcription and involves nuclear protein exchange.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The histones are mostly displaced, and replaced by protamines (small, arginine-rich proteins).
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] It is proposed that in yeast, regions devoid of histones become very fragile after transcription; HMO1, an HMG-box protein, helps in stabilizing nucleosomes-free chromatin.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] A variety of internal and external agents can cause DNA damage in cells.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Many factors influence how the repair route is selected, including the cell cycle phase and chromatin segment where the break occurred.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] In terms of initiating 5' end DNA repair, the p53 binding protein 1 (53BP1) and BRCA1 are important protein components that influence double-strand break repair pathway selection.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The 53BP1 complex attaches to chromatin near DNA breaks and activates downstream factors such as Rap1-Interacting Factor 1 (RIF1) and shieldin, which protects DNA ends against nucleolytic destruction.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] DNA damage process occurs within the condition of chromatin, and the constantly changing chromatin environment has a large effect on it.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Accessing and repairing the damaged cell of DNA, the genome condenses into chromatin and repairing it through modifying the histone residues.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Through altering the chromatin structure, histones residues are adding chemical groups namely phosphate, acetyl and one or more methyl groups and these control the expressions of gene building by proteins to acquire DNA.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Moreover, resynthesis of the delighted zone, DNA will be repaired by processing and restructuring the damaged bases.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] In order to maintain genomic integrity, "homologous recombination and classical non-homologous end joining process" has been followed by DNA to be repaired.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The packaging of eukaryotic DNA into chromatin presents a barrier to all DNA-based processes that require recruitment of enzymes to their sites of action.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] To allow the critical cellular process of DNA repair, the chromatin must be remodeled.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] In eukaryotes, ATP-dependent chromatin remodeling complexes and histone-modifying enzymes are two predominant factors employed to accomplish this remodeling process.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Chromatin relaxation occurs rapidly at the site of DNA damage.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] This process is initiated by PARP1 protein that starts to appear at DNA damage in less than a second, with half maximum accumulation within 1.6 seconds after the damage occurs.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] Next the chromatin remodeler Alc1 quickly attaches to the product of PARP1, and completes arrival at the DNA damage within 10 seconds of the damage.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] About half of the maximum chromatin relaxation, presumably due to action of Alc1, occurs by 10 seconds.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] This then allows recruitment of the DNA repair enzyme MRE11, to initiate DNA repair, within 13 seconds.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] γH2AX, the phosphorylated form of H2AX is also involved in the early steps leading to chromatin decondensation after DNA damage occurrence.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The histone variant H2AX constitutes about 10% of the H2A histones in human chromatin. γH2AX (H2AX phosphorylated on serine 139) can be detected as soon as 20 seconds after irradiation of cells (with DNA double-strand break formation), and half maximum accumulation of γH2AX occurs in one minute.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The extent of chromatin with phosphorylated γH2AX is about two million base pairs at the site of a DNA double-strand break. γH2AX does not, itself, cause chromatin decondensation, but within 30 seconds of irradiation, RNF8 protein can be detected in association with γH2AX.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] RNF8 mediates extensive chromatin decondensation, through its subsequent interaction with CHD4, a component of the nucleosome remodeling and deacetylase complex NuRD.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] After undergoing relaxation subsequent to DNA damage, followed by DNA repair, chromatin recovers to a compaction state close to its pre-damage level after about 20 min.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] **DNase-seq** (DNase I hypersensitive sites Sequencing) uses the sensitivity of accessible regions in the genome to the DNase I enzyme to map open or accessible regions in the genome.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] **FAIRE-seq** (Formaldehyde-Assisted Isolation of Regulatory Elements sequencing) uses the chemical properties of protein-bound DNA in a two-phase separation method to extract nucleosome depleted regions from the genome.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] **ATAC-seq** (Assay for Transposable Accessible Chromatin sequencing) uses the Tn5 transposase to integrate (synthetic) transposons into accessible regions of the genome consequentially highlighting the localisation of nucleosomes and transcription factors across the genome.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] **DNA footprinting** is a method aimed at identifying protein-bound DNA.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] It uses labeling and fragmentation coupled to gel electrophoresis to identify areas of the genome that have been bound by proteins.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] **MNase-seq** (Micrococcal Nuclease sequencing) uses the micrococcal nuclease enzyme to identify nucleosome positioning throughout the genome.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] **Chromosome conformation capture** determines the spatial organization of chromatin in the nucleus, by inferring genomic locations that physically interact.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] **MACC profiling** (Micrococcal nuclease ACCessibility profiling) uses titration series of chromatin digests with micrococcal nuclease to identify chromatin accessibility as well as to map nucleosomes and non-histone DNA-binding proteins in both open and closed regions of the genome.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] It has been a puzzle how decondensed interphase chromosomes remain essentially unknotted.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The natural expectation is that in the presence of type II DNA topoisomerases that permit passages of double-stranded DNA regions through each other, all chromosomes should reach the state of topological equilibrium.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] The topological equilibrium in highly crowded interphase chromosomes forming chromosome territories would result in formation of highly knotted chromatin fibres.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] However, Chromosome Conformation Capture (3C) methods revealed that the decay of contacts with the genomic distance in interphase chromosomes is practically the same as in the crumpled globule state that is formed when long polymers condense without formation of any knots.
[src:atac-seq/chromatin] It has been shown that the process of chromatin-loop extrusion is ideally suited to actively unknot chromatin fibres in interphase chromosomes.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] In genetics, **DNase I hypersensitive sites** (**DHSs**) are regions of chromatin that are sensitive to cleavage by the DNase I enzyme.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] In these specific regions of the genome, chromatin has lost its condensed structure, exposing the DNA and making it accessible.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] This raises the availability of DNA to degradation by enzymes, such as DNase I.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] These accessible chromatin zones are functionally related to transcriptional activity, since this remodeled state is necessary for the binding of proteins such as transcription factors.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] Since the discovery of DHSs 30 years ago, they have been used as markers of regulatory DNA regions.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] These regions have been shown to map many types of cis-regulatory elements including promoters, enhancers, insulators, silencers and locus control regions.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] A high-throughput measure of these regions is available through DNase-Seq.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] The ENCODE project proposes to map all of the DHSs in the human genome with the intention of cataloging human regulatory DNA.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] DHSs mark transcriptionally active regions of the genome, where there will be cellular selectivity.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] So, they used 125 different human cell types.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] This way, using the massive sequencing technique, they obtained the DHSs profiles of every cellular type.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] Through an analysis of the data, they identified almost 2.9 million distinct DHSs.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] 34% were specific to each cell type, and only a small minority (3,692) were detected in all cell types.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] Also, it was confirmed that only 5% of DHSs were found in TSS (Transcriptional Start Site) regions.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] The remaining 95% represented distal DHSs, divided in a uniform way between intronic and intergenic regions.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] The data gives an idea of the great complexity regulating the genetic expression in the human genome and the quantity of elements that control this regulation.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] The high-resolution mapping of DHSs in the model plant Arabidopsis thaliana has been reported.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] Total 38,290 and 41,193 DHSs in leaf and flower tissues have been identified, respectively.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] The data obtained were validated with the chromosome conformation capture carbon copy (5C) technique.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] This technique is based in the physical association that exists between the promoter and the enhancers, determining the regions of chromatin that enter in contact in the promoter/enhancer connections.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] It was confirmed that the majority of promoters were related with more than one enhancer, which indicates the existence of a complicated network of regulation for the immense majority of genes.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] Surprisingly, they also found that approximately half of the enhancers were found to be associated with more than one promoter.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] This discovery shows that the human cis-regulatory system is much more complicated than initially thought.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] The number of distal cis-regulatory elements connected to a promoter is related to the quantitative average of the regulation complexity of a gene.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] In this way, it was determined that human genes with more interactions with distal DHSs, and with at least one more complex regulation, corresponded with those genes with functions in the immune system.
[src:atac-seq/dnase-i-hypersensitive-site] This indicates that the complex of cellular and environmental signals processed by the immune system is directly encoded in the cis-regulatory architecture of its constituent genes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] A **nucleosome** is the basic structural unit of DNA packaging in eukaryotes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The structure of a nucleosome consists of a segment of DNA wound around eight histone proteins and resembles thread wrapped around a spool.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The nucleosome is the fundamental subunit of chromatin.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Each nucleosome is composed of a little less than two turns of DNA wrapped around a set of eight proteins called histones, which are known as a histone octamer.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Each histone octamer is composed of two copies each of the histone proteins H2A, H2B, H3, and H4.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] DNA must be compacted into nucleosomes to fit within the cell nucleus.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In addition to nucleosome wrapping, chromatin is further compacted by being folded into a series of more complex structures, eventually forming a chromosome.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Each human cell contains about 30 million nucleosomes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosomes are thought to carry epigenetically inherited information in the form of covalent modifications of their core histones.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosome positions in the genome are not random, and it is important to know where each nucleosome is located because this determines the accessibility of the DNA to regulatory proteins.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosomes were first observed as particles in the electron microscope by Don and Ada Olins in 1974, and their existence and structure (as histone octamers surrounded by approximately 200 base pairs of DNA) were proposed by Roger Kornberg.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The role of the nucleosome as a regulator of transcription was demonstrated by Lorch et al. in vitro in 1987 and by Han and Grunstein and Clark-Adams et al. in vivo in 1988.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The nucleosome core particle consists of approximately 146 base pairs (bp) of DNA wrapped in 1.67 left-handed superhelical turns around a histone octamer, consisting of 2 copies each of the core histones H2A, H2B, H3, and H4.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Core particles are connected by stretches of linker DNA, which can be up to about 80 bp long.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Technically, a nucleosome is defined as the core particle plus one of these linker regions; however the word is often synonymous with the core particle.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Genome-wide nucleosome positioning maps are now available for many model organisms and human cells.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Linker histones such as H1 and its isoforms are involved in chromatin compaction and sit at the base of the nucleosome near the DNA entry and exit binding to the linker region of the DNA.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Non-condensed nucleosomes without the linker histone resemble "beads on a string of DNA" under an electron microscope.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In contrast to most eukaryotic cells, mature sperm cells largely use protamines to package their genomic DNA, most likely to achieve an even higher packaging ratio.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Histone equivalents and a simplified chromatin structure have also been found in Archaea, suggesting that eukaryotes are not the only organisms that use nucleosomes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Pioneering structural studies in the 1980s by Aaron Klug's group provided the first evidence that an octamer of histone proteins wraps DNA around itself in about 1.7 turns of a left-handed superhelix.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In 1997 the first near atomic resolution crystal structure of the nucleosome was solved by the Richmond group at the ETH Zurich, showing the most important details of the particle.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The human alpha satellite palindromic DNA critical to achieving the 1997 nucleosome crystal structure was developed by the Bunick group at Oak Ridge National Laboratory in Tennessee.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The structures of over 20 different nucleosome core particles have been solved to date, including those containing histone variants and histones from different species.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The structure of the nucleosome core particle is remarkably conserved, and even a change of over 100 residues between frog and yeast histones results in electron density maps with an overall root mean square deviation of only 1.6Å.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The nucleosome core particle (shown in the figure) consists of about 146 base pair of DNA wrapped in 1.67 left-handed superhelical turns around the histone octamer, consisting of 2 copies each of the core histones H2A, H2B, H3, and H4.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Adjacent nucleosomes are joined by a stretch of free DNA termed linker DNA (which varies from 10 - 80 bp in length depending on species and tissue type).The whole structure generates a cylinder of diameter 11 nm and a height of 5.5 nm.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosome core particles are observed when chromatin in interphase is treated to cause the chromatin to unfold partially.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The resulting image, via an electron microscope, is "beads on a string".
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The string is the DNA, while each bead in the nucleosome is a core particle.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The nucleosome core particle is composed of DNA and histone proteins.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Partial DNAse digestion of chromatin reveals its nucleosome structure.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Because DNA portions of nucleosome core particles are less accessible for DNAse than linking sections, DNA gets digested into fragments of lengths equal to multiplicity of distance between nucleosomes (180, 360, 540 base pairs etc.).
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Hence a very characteristic pattern similar to a ladder is visible during gel electrophoresis of that DNA.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Such digestion can occur also under natural conditions during apoptosis ("cell suicide" or programmed cell death), because autodestruction of DNA typically is its role.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The core histone proteins contains a characteristic structural motif termed the "histone fold", which consists of three alpha-helices (α1-3) separated by two loops (L1-2).
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In solution, the histones form H2A-H2B heterodimers and H3-H4 heterotetramers.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Histones dimerise about their long α2 helices in an anti-parallel orientation, and, in the case of H3 and H4, two such dimers form a 4-helix bundle stabilised by extensive H3-H3' interaction.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The H2A/H2B dimer binds onto the H3/H4 tetramer due to interactions between H4 and H2B, which include the formation of a hydrophobic cluster.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The histone octamer is formed by a central H3/H4 tetramer sandwiched between two H2A/H2B dimers.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Due to the highly basic charge of all four core histones, the histone octamer is stable only in the presence of DNA or very high salt concentrations.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The nucleosome contains over 120 direct protein-DNA interactions and several hundred water-mediated ones.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Direct protein - DNA interactions are not spread evenly about the octamer surface but rather located at discrete sites.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] These are due to the formation of two types of DNA binding sites within the octamer; the α1α1 site, which uses the α1 helix from two adjacent histones, and the L1L2 site formed by the L1 and L2 loops.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Salt links and hydrogen bonding between both side-chain basic and hydroxyl groups and main-chain amides with the DNA backbone phosphates form the bulk of interactions with the DNA.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This is important, given that the ubiquitous distribution of nucleosomes along genomes requires it to be a non-sequence-specific DNA-binding factor.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Although nucleosomes tend to prefer some DNA sequences over others, they are capable of binding practically to any sequence, which is thought to be due to the flexibility in the formation of these water-mediated interactions.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In addition, non-polar interactions are made between protein side-chains and the deoxyribose groups, and an arginine side-chain intercalates into the DNA minor groove at all 14 sites where it faces the octamer surface.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The distribution and strength of DNA-binding sites about the octamer surface distorts the DNA within the nucleosome core.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The DNA is non-uniformly bent and also contains twist defects.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The twist of free B-form DNA in solution is 10.5 bp per turn.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] However, the overall twist of nucleosomal DNA is only 10.2 bp per turn, varying from a value of 9.4 to 10.9 bp per turn.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The histone tail extensions constitute up to 30% by mass of histones, but are not visible in the crystal structures of nucleosomes due to their high intrinsic flexibility, and have been thought to be largely unstructured.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The N-terminal tails of histones H3 and H2B pass through a channel formed by the minor grooves of the two DNA strands, protruding from the DNA every 20 bp.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This interaction is thought to occur under physiological conditions also, and suggests that acetylation of the H4 tail distorts the higher-order structure of chromatin.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The organization of the DNA that is achieved by the nucleosome cannot fully explain the packaging of DNA observed in the cell nucleus.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Further compaction of chromatin into the cell nucleus is necessary, but it is not yet well understood.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The current understanding is that repeating nucleosomes with intervening "linker" DNA form a *10-nm-fiber*, described as "beads on a string", and have a packing ratio of about five to ten.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] A chain of nucleosomes can be arranged in a *30 nm fiber*, a compacted structure with a packing ratio of ~50 and whose formation is dependent on the presence of the H1 histone.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] A crystal structure of a tetranucleosome has been presented and used to build up a proposed structure of the 30 nm fiber as a two-start helix.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] There is still a certain amount of contention regarding this model, as it is incompatible with recent electron microscopy data.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Beyond this, the structure of chromatin is poorly understood, but it is classically suggested that the 30 nm fiber is arranged into loops along a central protein scaffold to form transcriptionally active euchromatin.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Further compaction leads to transcriptionally inactive heterochromatin.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Although the nucleosome is a very stable protein-DNA complex, it is not static and has been shown to undergo a number of different structural re-arrangements including nucleosome sliding and DNA site exposure.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Depending on the context, nucleosomes can inhibit or facilitate transcription factor binding.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosome positions are controlled by three major contributions: First, the intrinsic binding affinity of the histone octamer depends on the DNA sequence.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Second, the nucleosome can be displaced or recruited by the competitive or cooperative binding of other protein factors.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Third, the nucleosome may be actively translocated by ATP-dependent remodeling complexes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] When incubated thermally, nucleosomes reconstituted onto the 5S DNA positioning sequence were able to reposition themselves translationally onto adjacent sequences.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This repositioning does not require disruption of the histone octamer but is consistent with nucleosomes being able to "slide" along the DNA *in cis*.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] CTCF binding sites act as nucleosome positioning anchors so that, when used to align various genomic signals, multiple flanking nucleosomes can be readily identified.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Although nucleosomes are intrinsically mobile, eukaryotes have evolved a large family of ATP-dependent chromatin remodelling enzymes to alter chromatin structure, many of which do so via nucleosome sliding.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosome sliding is one of the possible mechanism for large scale tissue specific expression of genes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The transcription start site for genes expressed in a particular tissue, are nucleosome depleted while, the same set of genes in other tissue where they are not expressed, are nucleosome bound.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosomal DNA is in equilibrium between a wrapped and unwrapped state.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] DNA within the nucleosome remains fully wrapped for only 250 ms before it is unwrapped for 10-50 ms and then rapidly rewrapped, as measured using time-resolved FRET.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This implies that DNA does not need to be actively dissociated from the nucleosome but that there is a significant fraction of time during which it is fully accessible.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Introducing a DNA-binding sequence within the nucleosome increases the accessibility of adjacent regions of DNA when bound.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This propensity for DNA within the nucleosome to "breathe" has important functional consequences for all DNA-binding proteins that operate in a chromatin environment.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In particular, the dynamic breathing of nucleosomes plays an important role in restricting the advancement of RNA polymerase II during transcription elongation.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Promoters of active genes have nucleosome free regions (NFR).
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This allows for promoter DNA accessibility to various proteins, such as transcription factors.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosome free region typically spans for 200 nucleotides in *S. cerevisiae* Well-positioned nucleosomes form boundaries of NFR.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] These nucleosomes are called +1-nucleosome and −1-nucleosome and are located at canonical distances downstream and upstream, respectively, from transcription start site. +1-nucleosome and several downstream nucleosomes also tend to incorporate H2A.Z histone variant.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Eukaryotic genomes are ubiquitously associated into chromatin; however, cells must spatially and temporally regulate specific loci independently of bulk chromatin.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In order to achieve the high level of control required to co-ordinate nuclear processes such as DNA replication, repair, and transcription, cells have developed a variety of means to locally and specifically modulate chromatin structure and function.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This can involve covalent modification of histones, the incorporation of histone variants, and non-covalent remodelling by ATP-dependent remodeling enzymes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Since they were discovered in the mid-1960s, histone modifications have been predicted to affect transcription.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The fact that most of the early post-translational modifications found were concentrated within the tail extensions that protrude from the nucleosome core led to two main theories regarding the mechanism of histone modification.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The first of the theories suggested that they may affect electrostatic interactions between the histone tails and DNA to "loosen" chromatin structure.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Later it was proposed that combinations of these modifications may create binding epitopes with which to recruit other proteins.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Recently, given that more modifications have been found in the structured regions of histones, it has been put forward that these modifications may affect histone-DNA and histone-histone interactions within the nucleosome core.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Modifications (such as acetylation or phosphorylation) that lower the charge of the globular histone core are predicted to "loosen" core-DNA association; the strength of the effect depends on location of the modification within the core.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Some modifications have been shown to be correlated with gene silencing; others seem to be correlated with gene activation.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Common modifications include acetylation, methylation, or ubiquitination of lysine; methylation of arginine; and phosphorylation of serine.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The information stored in this way is considered epigenetic, since it is not encoded in the DNA but is still inherited to daughter cells.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The maintenance of a repressed or activated status of a gene is often necessary for cellular differentiation.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Although histones are remarkably conserved throughout evolution, several variant forms have been identified.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This diversification of histone function is restricted to H2A and H3, with H2B and H4 being mostly invariant.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] H2A can be replaced by H2AZ (which leads to reduced nucleosome stability) or H2AX (which is associated with DNA repair and T cell differentiation), whereas the inactive X chromosomes in mammals are enriched in macroH2A.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] H3 can be replaced by H3.3 (which correlates with activate genes and regulatory elements) and in centromeres H3 is replaced by CENPA.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Also viruses can form nucleosome particles that include variants of canonical histones, which are sometimes fused in doublets in the same polipeptide chain thus giving place to a double histone fold.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] A number of distinct reactions are associated with the term ATP-dependent chromatin remodeling.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Remodeling enzymes have been shown to slide nucleosomes along DNA, disrupt histone-DNA contacts to the extent of destabilizing the H2A/H2B dimer and to generate negative superhelical torsion in DNA and chromatin.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Recently, the Swr1 remodeling enzyme has been shown to introduce the variant histone H2A.Z into nucleosomes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] At present, it is not clear if all of these represent distinct reactions or merely alternative outcomes of a common mechanism.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] What is shared between all, and indeed the hallmark of ATP-dependent chromatin remodeling, is that they all result in altered DNA accessibility.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Studies looking at gene activation *in vivo* and, more astonishingly, remodeling *in vitro* have revealed that chromatin remodeling events and transcription-factor binding are cyclical and periodic in nature.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] While the consequences of this for the reaction mechanism of chromatin remodeling are not known, the dynamic nature of the system may allow it to respond faster to external stimuli.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] A recent study indicates that nucleosome positions change significantly during mouse embryonic stem cell development, and these changes are related to binding of developmental transcription factors.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Studies in 2007 have catalogued nucleosome positions in yeast and shown that nucleosomes are depleted in promoter regions and origins of replication.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] About 80% of the yeast genome appears to be covered by nucleosomes and the pattern of nucleosome positioning clearly relates to DNA regions that regulate transcription, regions that are transcribed and regions that initiate DNA replication.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Most recently, a new study examined *dynamic changes* in nucleosome repositioning during a global transcriptional reprogramming event to elucidate the effects on nucleosome displacement during genome-wide transcriptional changes in yeast (*Saccharomyces cerevisiae*).
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The results suggested that nucleosomes that were localized to promoter regions are displaced in response to stress (like heat shock).
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In addition, the removal of nucleosomes usually corresponded to transcriptional activation and the replacement of nucleosomes usually corresponded to transcriptional repression, presumably because transcription factor binding sites became more or less accessible, respectively.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In general, only one or two nucleosomes were repositioned at the promoter to effect these transcriptional changes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] However, even in chromosomal regions that were not associated with transcriptional changes, nucleosome repositioning was observed, suggesting that the covering and uncovering of transcriptional DNA does not necessarily produce a transcriptional event.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] After transcription, the rDNA region has to protected from any damage, it suggested HMGB proteins play a major role in protecting the nucleosome free region.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] DNA twist defects are when the addition of one or a few base pairs from one DNA segment are transferred to the next segment resulting in a change of the DNA twist.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This will not only change the twist of the DNA but it will also change the length.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] This twist defect eventually moves around the nucleosome through the transferring of the base pair, this means DNA twists can cause nucleosome sliding.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosome crystal structures have shown that superhelix location 2 and 5 on the nucleosome are commonly found to be where DNA twist defects occur as these are common remodeler binding sites.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] There are a variety of chromatin remodelers but all share the existence of an ATPase motor which facilitates chromatin sliding on DNA through the binding and hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] When the ATPase motor is changing from open and closed states, the DNA duplex changes geometry and exhibits base pair tilting.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The initiation of the twist defects via the ATPase motor causes tension to accumulate around the remodeler site.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The tension is released when the sliding of DNA has been completed throughout the nucleosome via the spread of two twist defects (one on each strand) in opposite directions.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosomes can be assembled *in vitro* by either using purified native or recombinant histones.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] One standard technique of loading the DNA around the histones involves the use of salt dialysis.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] A reaction consisting of the histone octamers and a naked DNA template can be incubated together at a salt concentration of 2 M.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] By steadily decreasing the salt concentration, the DNA will equilibrate to a position where it is wrapped around the histone octamers, forming nucleosomes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In appropriate conditions, this reconstitution process allows for the nucleosome positioning affinity of a given sequence to be mapped experimentally.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] A recent advance in the production of nucleosome core particles with enhanced stability involves site-specific disulfide crosslinks.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Two different crosslinks can be introduced into the nucleosome core particle.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] A first one crosslinks the two copies of H2A via an introduced cysteine (N38C) resulting in histone octamer which is stable against H2A/H2B dimer loss during nucleosome reconstitution.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] A second crosslink can be introduced between the H3 N-terminal histone tail and the nucleosome DNA ends via an incorporated convertible nucleotide.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The DNA-histone octamer crosslink stabilizes the nucleosome core particle against DNA dissociation at very low particle concentrations and at elevated salt concentrations.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosomes are the basic packing unit of genomic DNA built from histone proteins around which DNA is coiled.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] They serve as a scaffold for formation of higher order chromatin structure as well as for a layer of regulatory control of gene expression.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Nucleosomes are quickly assembled onto newly synthesized DNA behind the replication fork.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Histones H3 and H4 from disassembled old nucleosomes are kept in the vicinity and randomly distributed on the newly synthesized DNA.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] They are assembled by the chromatin assembly factor 1 (CAF-1) complex, which consists of three subunits (p150, p60, and p48).
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Newly synthesized H3 and H4 are assembled by the replication coupling assembly factor (RCAF).
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] RCAF contains the subunit Asf1, which binds to newly synthesized H3 and H4 proteins.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The old H3 and H4 proteins retain their chemical modifications which contributes to the passing down of the epigenetic signature.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The newly synthesized H3 and H4 proteins are gradually acetylated at different lysine residues as part of the chromatin maturation process.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] It is also thought that the old H3 and H4 proteins in the new nucleosomes recruit histone modifying enzymes that mark the new histones, contributing to epigenetic memory.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] In contrast to old H3 and H4, the old H2A and H2B histone proteins are released and degraded; therefore, newly assembled H2A and H2B proteins are incorporated into new nucleosomes.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] H2A and H2B are assembled into dimers which are then loaded onto nucleosomes by the nucleosome assembly protein-1 (NAP-1) which also assists with nucleosome sliding.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The nucleosomes are also spaced by ATP-dependent nucleosome-remodeling complexes containing enzymes such as Isw1 Ino80, and Chd1, and subsequently assembled into higher order structure.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] The crystal structure of the nucleosome core particle (PDB: 1EQZ) - different views showing details of histone folding and organization.
[src:atac-seq/nucleosome] Histones H2A, H2B, H3, H4 and DNA are coloured.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The discovery of transposable elements (TEs) by Barbara McClintock came many decades before during McClintock's early studies at the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory (CSH) in New York.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Here, McClintock identified TEs in maize (*Zea mays*) during experimentation with plants which presented evidence of breaks in their chromosomes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] In the winter of 1944–1945, McClintock planted corn kernels that were self-pollinated, meaning that the silk (style) of the flower received pollen from its own anther.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] These kernels came from a long line of plants that had been self-pollinated, causing broken arms on the end of their ninth chromosomes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] As the plants began to grow, McClintock noted unusual color patterns on the leaves; for example, one leaf had two albino patches of almost identical size, located side by side on the leaf.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] McClintock hypothesized that during cell division certain cells lost genetic material, while others gained what they had lost.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] However, when comparing the chromosomes of the current generation of plants with the parent generation, she found certain parts of the chromosome had switched position.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] This refuted the popular genetic theory of the time that genes were fixed in their position on a chromosome.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] McClintock found that genes could not only move but they could also be turned on or off due to certain environmental conditions or during different stages of cell development.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] She also showed that these gene mutations could be reversed.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] In 1950, McClintock published her findings in *The Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences* (PNAS), in an article titled "The Origin and Behavior of Mutable Loci in Maize".
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] At the 1951 Cold Spring Harbor Symposium, where she first publicized her findings, her talk was met with silence.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Her work was largely dismissed and ignored until the late 1960s–1970s when after TEs were found in bacteria, their presence in eukaryotes was rediscovered.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] McClintock was awarded a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1983 for her discovery of TEs, more than thirty years after her initial research.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Transposable elements represent one of several types of mobile genetic elements.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] TEs are assigned to one of two classes according to their mechanism of transposition, which can be described as either "*copy and paste"* (Class I TEs) or "*cut and paste"* (Class II TEs).
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Class I TEs are copied in two stages: first, they are transcribed from DNA to RNA, and the RNA produced is then reverse transcribed to DNA.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] RNA conversion back into DNA is then facilitated through an enzyme called reverse transcriptase which is often encoded by the TE itself.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] This newly copied DNA is then inserted back into the genome at a new position.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The characteristics of retrotransposons are similar to retroviruses, such as HIV as HIV utilizes reverse transcriptase to make a double strand copy of its RNA genome which is then integrated into the host cells genome.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Despite the potential negative effects of retrotransposons self insertion into necessary DNA sequences, which can result in important genes becoming unusable, they are essential in keeping different species' ribosomal DNA (rDNA) intact over the generations, preventing infertility.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The R2 retrotransposon of *Drosophila* creates double-stranded breaks by endonuclease activity during its process of replication within its target rDNA, allowing for homologous recombination between sister chromatids to repair the breaks.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The resulting chromatids, each with different quantities of rDNA, are tagged and differentially segregated during asymmetric division of progenitors into daughter stem cells, which receive the chromatids with more rDNA, and germ cell precursors.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Long interspersed nuclear clusters encode for reverse transcriptase and are transcribed by RNA polymerase II.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Meanwhile SINEs do not encode for reverse transcriptase and are transcribed by RNA polymerase III.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The cut-and-paste transposition mechanism of class II TEs does not involve an RNA intermediate.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The transpositions are catalyzed by several transposase enzymes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Some transposases non-specifically bind to any target site in DNA, whereas others bind to specific target sequences.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The transposase makes a staggered cut at the target site producing sticky ends, cuts out the DNA transposon and ligates it into the target site.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] A DNA polymerase fills in the resulting gaps from the sticky ends and DNA ligase closes the sugar-phosphate backbone.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] This results in target site duplication and the insertion sites of DNA transposons may be identified by short direct repeats (a staggered cut in the target DNA filled by DNA polymerase) followed by inverted repeats (which are important for the TE excision by transposase).
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Cut-and-paste TEs may be duplicated if their transposition takes place during S phase of the cell cycle, when a donor site has already been replicated but a target site has not yet been replicated.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Such duplications at the target site can result in gene duplication, which plays an important role in genomic evolution.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Not all DNA transposons transpose through the cut-and-paste mechanism.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] In some cases, a replicative transposition is observed in which a "complex transposon" replicates itself to a new target site (e.g. helitron).
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Class II TEs comprise less than 2% of the human genome, making the other transposons Class I.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Transposition can be classified as either "autonomous" or "non-autonomous" in both Class I and Class II TEs.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Autonomous TEs can move through the genome by themselves as they encode for their transpositional machinery allowing for their ability to move around the genome.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] This is contrasted by non-autonomous where they lack the ability to encode for their transposition machinery and require the presence of another TE machinery to move.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] This is often because dependent TEs lack transposase (for Class II) or reverse transcriptase (for Class I).
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Activator element (*Ac*) is an example of an autonomous TE, and dissociation elements (*Ds*) is an example of a non-autonomous TE.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Without *Ac,* *Ds* is not able to transpose.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Transposable elements can be all over a genome, and in the case of maize, TEs make up 50% of the genome.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] In yeast (which has 5 classes of retrotransposons, Ty1-Ty5), over 90% of the Ty1 through T4 elements are located within 750 bp upstream of genes transcribed by RNA polymerase III, particularly tRNA genes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The Ty5 elements are all located at the telomeres or regions with telomeric chromatin.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] TEs are found in almost all life forms, and the scientific community is still exploring their evolution and their effect on genome evolution.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] It is unclear whether TEs originated in the last universal common ancestor, arose independently multiple times, or arose once and then spread to other kingdoms by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Because excessive TE activity can damage exons, many organisms have acquired mechanisms to inhibit their activity.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Bacteria may undergo high rates of gene deletion as part of a mechanism to remove TEs and viruses from their genomes, while eukaryotic organisms typically use RNA interference to inhibit TE activity.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Nevertheless, some TEs generate large families often associated with speciation events.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Evolution often deactivates DNA transposons, leaving them as introns (inactive gene sequences).
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] In vertebrate animal cells, nearly all 100,000+ DNA transposons per genome have genes that encode inactive transposase polypeptides.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The first synthetic transposon designed for use in vertebrate (including human) cells, the Sleeping Beauty transposon system, is a Tc1/mariner-like transposon.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Its dead ("fossil") versions are spread widely in the salmonid genome and a functional version was engineered by comparing those versions.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Human Tc1-like transposons are divided into Hsmar1 and Hsmar2 subfamilies.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Although both types are inactive, one copy of Hsmar1 found in the SETMAR gene is under selection as it provides DNA-binding for the histone-modifying protein.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Many other human genes are similarly derived from transposons.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Hsmar2 has been reconstructed multiple times from the fossil sequences.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] TEs may affect gene regulatory networks and thus have evolutionary advantages.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Interspersed repeats are created by transposition; since they can inhibit gene conversion, they protect novel gene sequences from being overwritten by similar gene sequences and thereby facilitate the development of new genes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] TEs may also have been co-opted by the vertebrate immune system as a means of producing antibody diversity.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The V(D)J recombination system operates by a mechanism similar to that of some TEs.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] TEs also serve to generate repeating sequences that can form dsRNA to act as a substrate for the action of ADAR in RNA editing.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] TEs can contain many types of genes, including those conferring antibiotic resistance and the ability to transpose to conjugative plasmids.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Some TEs also contain integrons, genetic elements that can capture and express genes from other sources.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] These contain integrase, which can integrate gene cassettes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] There are over 40 antibiotic resistance genes identified on cassettes, as well as virulence genes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Transposons do not always excise their elements precisely, sometimes removing the adjacent base pairs; this can lead to merged exons in a process called exon shuffling.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Shuffling two unrelated exons can create a novel gene product or, more likely, an intron.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Some non-autonomous DNA TEs found in plants can capture coding DNA from genes and shuffle them across the genome.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] This process can duplicate genes in the genome (a phenomenon called transduplication), and can contribute to generate novel genes by exon shuffling.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] There is a hypothesis that TEs might provide a ready source of DNA that could be co-opted by the cell to help regulate gene expression.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Research showed that many diverse modes of TEs co-evolution along with some transcription factors targeting TE-associated genomic elements and chromatin are evolving from TE sequences.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Most of the time, these particular modes do not follow the simple model of TEs and regulating host gene expression.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] One study estimated the rate of transposition of a particular retrotransposon, the Ty1 element in *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Using several assumptions, the rate of successful transposition event per single Ty1 element came out to be about once every few months to once every few years.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Some TEs contain heat-shock like promoters and their rate of transposition increases if the cell is subjected to stress, thus increasing the mutation rate under these conditions, which might be beneficial to the cell.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] One hypothesis suggests that only approximately 100 LINE1 related sequences are active, despite their sequences making up 17% of the human genome.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] In human cells, silencing of LINE1 sequences is triggered by an RNA interference (RNAi) mechanism.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Surprisingly, the RNAi sequences are derived from the 5′ untranslated region (UTR) of the LINE1, a long terminal which repeats itself.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Supposedly, the 5′ LINE1 UTR that codes for the sense promoter for LINE1 transcription also encodes the antisense promoter for the miRNA that becomes the substrate for siRNA production.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Inhibition of the RNAi silencing mechanism in this region showed an increase in LINE1 transcription.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Cells defend against the proliferation of TEs in a number of ways.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] These include piRNAs and siRNAs, which silence TEs after they have been transcribed.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Certain mutated plants have been found to have defects in methylation-related enzymes (methyl transferase) which cause the transcription of TEs, thus affecting the phenotype.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The second step of *de novo* repeat identification involves building a consensus of each family of sequences.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] A consensus sequence is a sequence that is created based on the repeats that comprise a TE family.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] A base pair in a consensus is the one that occurred most often in the sequences being compared to make the consensus.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Once a consensus sequence has been made for each family, it is then possible to move on to further analysis, such as TE classification and genome masking in order to quantify the overall TE content of the genome.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Transposable elements have been recognized as good candidates for stimulating gene adaptation, through their ability to regulate the expression levels of nearby genes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Combined with their "mobility", transposable elements can be relocated adjacent to their targeted genes, and control the expression levels of the gene, dependent upon the circumstances.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The study conducted in 2008, "High Rate of Recent Transposable Element–Induced Adaptation in Drosophila melanogaster", used *D. melanogaster* that had recently migrated from Africa to other parts of the world, as a basis for studying adaptations caused by transposable elements.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Although most of the TEs were located on introns, the experiment showed a significant difference in gene expressions between the population in Africa and other parts of the world.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The four TEs that caused the selective sweep were more prevalent in *D. melanogaster* from temperate climates, leading the researchers to conclude that the selective pressures of the climate prompted genetic adaptation.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] From this experiment, it has been confirmed that adaptive TEs are prevalent in nature, by enabling organisms to adapt gene expression as a result of new selective pressures.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] However, not all effects of adaptive TEs are beneficial to the population.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] In the research conducted in 2009, "A Recent Adaptive Transposable Element Insertion Near Highly Conserved Developmental Loci in Drosophila melanogaster", a TE, inserted between Jheh 2 and Jheh 3, revealed a downgrade in the expression level of both of the genes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Downregulation of such genes has caused *Drosophila* to exhibit extended developmental time and reduced egg to adult viability.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Although this adaptation was observed in high frequency in all non-African populations, it was not fixed in any of them.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] This is not hard to believe, since it is logical for a population to favor higher egg to adult viability, therefore trying to purge the trait caused by this specific TE adaptation.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] At the same time, there have been several reports showing the advantageous adaptation caused by TEs.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] In the research done with silkworms, "An Adaptive Transposable Element insertion in the Regulatory Region of the EO Gene in the Domesticated Silkworm", a TE insertion was observed in the cis-regulatory region of the EO gene, which regulates molting hormone 20E, and enhanced expression was recorded.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] While populations without the TE insert are often unable to effectively regulate hormone 20E under starvation conditions, those with the insert had a more stable development, which resulted in higher developmental uniformity.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] These three experiments all demonstrated different ways in which TE insertions can be advantageous or disadvantageous, through means of regulating the expression level of adjacent genes.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] The field of adaptive TE research is still under development and more findings can be expected in the future.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Recent studies have confirmed that TEs can contribute to the generation of transcription factors.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] However, how this process of contribution can have an impact on the participation of genome control networks.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] TEs are more common in many regions of the DNA and it makes up 45% of total human DNA.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] Also, TEs contributed to 16% of transcription factor binding sites.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] A larger number of motifs are also found in non-TE-derived DNA, and the number is larger than TE-derived DNA.
[src:atac-seq/transposable-element] All these factors correlate to the direct participation of TEs in many ways of gene control networks.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] A **transposase** is any of a class of enzymes capable of binding to the end of a transposon and catalysing its movement to another part of a genome, typically by a cut-and-paste mechanism or a replicative mechanism, in a process known as transposition.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The word "transposase" was coined by the individuals who cloned the enzyme required for transposition of the Tn3 transposon.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The existence of transposons was postulated in the late 1940s by Barbara McClintock, who was studying the inheritance of maize, but the actual molecular basis for transposition was described by later groups.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] McClintock discovered that some segments of chromosomes changed their position, jumping between different loci or from one chromosome to another.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The repositioning of these transposons (which coded for color) allowed other genes for pigment to be expressed.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Transposition in maize causes changes in color; however, in other organisms, such as bacteria, it can cause antibiotic resistance.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Transposition is also important in creating genetic diversity within species and generating adaptability to changing living conditions.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Transposases are classified under EC number EC 2.7.7.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Genes encoding transposases are widespread in the genomes of most organisms and are the most abundant genes known.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] During the course of human evolution, as much as 40% of the human genome has moved around via methods such as transposition of transposons.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Transposase (Tnp) Tn5 is a member of the RNase superfamily of proteins which includes retroviral integrases.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Tn5 can be found in *Shewanella* and *Escherichia* bacteria.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The transposon codes for antibiotic resistance to kanamycin and other aminoglycoside antibiotics.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Tn5 and other transposases are notably inactive.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Because DNA transposition events are inherently mutagenic, the low activity of transposases is necessary to reduce the risk of causing a fatal mutation in the host, and thus eliminating the transposable element.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] One of the reasons Tn5 is so unreactive is because the N- and C-termini are located in relatively close proximity to one another and tend to inhibit each other.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] This was elucidated by the characterization of several mutations which resulted in hyperactive forms of transposases.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] One such mutation, L372P, is a mutation of amino acid 372 in the Tn5 transposase.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] This amino acid is generally a leucine residue in the middle of an alpha helix.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] When this leucine is replaced with a proline residue the alpha helix is broken, introducing a conformational change to the C-terminal domain, separating it from the N-terminal domain enough to promote higher activity of the protein.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The transposition of a transposon often needs only three pieces: the transposon, the transposase enzyme, and the target DNA for the insertion of the transposon.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] This is the case with Tn5, which uses a cut-and-paste mechanism for moving around transposons.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Tn5 and most other transposases contain a DDE motif, which is the active site that catalyzes the movement of the transposon.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Aspartate-97, aspartate-188, and glutamate-326 make up the active site, which is a triad of acidic residues.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The DDE motif is said to coordinate divalent metal ions, most often magnesium and manganese, which are important in the catalytic reaction.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Because transposase is incredibly inactive, the DDE region is mutated so that the transposase becomes hyperactive and catalyzes the movement of the transposon.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The glutamate is transformed into an aspartate and the two aspartates into glutamates.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Through this mutation, the study of Tn5 becomes possible, but some steps in the catalytic process are lost as a result.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] There are several steps which catalyze the movement of the transposon, including Tnp binding, synapsis (the creation of a synaptic complex), cleavage, target capture, and strand transfer.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Transposase then binds to the DNA strand and creates a clamp over the transposon end of the DNA and inserts into the active site.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Once the transposase binds to the transposon, it produces a synaptic complex in which two transposases are bound in a cis/trans relationship with the transposon.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] In cleavage, the magnesium ions activate oxygen from water molecules and expose them to nucleophilic attack.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] This allows the water molecules to nick the 3' strands on both ends and create a hairpin formation, which separates the transposon from the donor DNA.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Next, the transposase moves the transposon to a suitable location.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Not much is known about the target capture, although there is a sequence bias which has not yet been determined.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] After target capture, the transposase attacks the target DNA nine base pairs apart, resulting in the integration of the transposon into the target DNA.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] As mentioned before, due to the mutations of the DDE, some steps of the process are lost—for example, when this experiment is performed *in vitro*, and SDS heat treatment denatures the transposase.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] However, it is still uncertain what happens to the transposase *in vivo*.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The study of transposase Tn5 is of general importance because of its similarities to HIV-1 and other retroviral diseases.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] By studying Tn5, much can also be discovered about other transposases and their activities.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Tn5 is utilized in genome sequencing by using the Tn5 to append sequencing adaptors and fragment the DNA in a single enzymatic reaction in 2010, reducing the time and input requirements over traditional next-generation sequencing library preparation.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The Tn5-based strategy can simplify the library preparation protocol significantly and can even be incorporated into the direct colony-PCR for large numbers of bacterial isolates with no obvious coverage bias.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The main disadvantages are less control of fragmented size compared to enzymatic fragmentation and mechanical fragmentation, and a bias toward high G-C content.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] This means of library preparation is also used in the ATAC-seq technique.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The Sleeping Beauty (SB) transposase is the recombinase that drives the Sleeping Beauty transposon system.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] SB transposase belongs to the DD[E/D] family of transposases, which in turn belong to a large superfamily of polynucleotidyl transferases that includes RNase H, RuvC Holliday resolvase, RAG proteins, and retroviral integrases.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The SB system is used primarily in vertebrate animals for gene transfer, including gene therapy, and gene discovery.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The engineered SB100X is an enzyme that directs the high levels of transposon integration.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The Tn7 transposon is a mobile genetic element found in many prokaryotes such as *Escherichia coli* (*E. coli*), and was first discovered as a DNA sequence in bacterial chromosomes and naturally occurring plasmids that encoded resistance to the antibiotics trimethoprim and streptomycin.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Specifically classified as a transposable element (transposon), the sequence can duplicate and move itself within a genome by utilizing a self-encoded recombinase enzyme called a transposase, resulting in effects such as creating or reversing mutations and changing genome size.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The Tn7 transposon has developed two mechanisms to promote its propagation among prokaryotes.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Like many other bacterial transposons, Tn7 transposes at low-frequency and inserts into many different sites with little to no site-selectivity.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Through this first pathway, Tn7 is preferentially directed into conjugable plasmids, which can be replicated and distributed between bacteria.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] However, Tn7 is unique in that it also transposes at high-frequency into a single specific site in bacterial chromosomes called attTn7.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] This specific sequence is an essential and highly conserved gene found in many strains of bacteria.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] However, the recombination is not deleterious to the host bacterium as Tn7 actually transposes downstream of the gene after recognizing it, resulting in a safe way to propagate the transposon without killing the host.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] This highly evolved and sophisticated target-site selection pathway suggests this pathway evolved to promote coexistence between the transposon and it host, as well as Tn7's successful transmission into future generations of bacterium.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The Tn7 transposon is 14 kb long and codes for five enzymes.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The ends of the DNA sequence consists of two segments that the Tn7 transposase interacts with during recombination.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The left segment (Tn7-L) is 150 bp long and the right sequence (Tn7-R) is 90 bp long.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Both ends of the transposon contain a series of 22 bp binding sites that the Tn7 transposase recognizes and binds to.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Within the transposon are five discrete genes encoding for proteins that make up the transposition machinery.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] In addition, the transposon contains an integron, a DNA segment containing several cassettes of genes encoding for antibiotic-resistance.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The Tn7 transposon codes for five proteins: TnsA, TnsB, TnsC, TnsD, and TnsE.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] TnsA and TnsB interact together to form the Tn7 transposase enzyme TnsAB.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The enzyme specifically recognizes and binds to the ends of the DNA sequence of the transposon, and excises it by introducing double-stranded DNA breaks to each end.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The excised sequence is then inserted to another target DNA site.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Much like other characterized transposons, the mechanism for Tn7 transposition involves cleavage of the 3' ends from the donating DNA by the TnsA protein of the TnsAB transposase.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] However, Tn7 is also uniquely cleaved near the 5' ends, about 5 bp from the 5' end towards the Tn7 transposon, by the TnsB protein of TnsAB.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] After the insertion of the transposon into the target DNA site, the 3' ends are covalently linked to the target DNA, but the 5 bp gaps are still present at the 5' ends.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] As a result, repair of these gaps leads to a further 5 bp duplication at the target site.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The TnsC protein interacts with the transposase enzyme and the target DNA to promote the excision and insertion processes.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The ability of TnsC to activate the transposase depends on its interaction with a target DNA along with its appropriate targeting protein, TnsD or TnsE.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The TnsD and TnsE proteins are alternative target selectors that are also DNA binding activators that promote excision and insertion of Tn7.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] Their ability to interact with a particular target DNA is key to the target-site selection of Tn7.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] The proteins TnsA, TnsB, and TnsC thus form the core machinery of Tn7: TnsA and TnsB interact together to form the transposase, while TnsC functions as a regulator of the transposase's activity, communicating between the transposase and TnsD and TnsE.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] When the TnsE protein interacts with the TnsABC core machinery, Tn7 preferentially directs insertions into conjugable plasmids.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] When the TnsD protein interacts with TnsABC, Tn7 preferentially directs insertions downstream into a single essential and highly conserved site in the bacterial chromosome.
[src:atac-seq/transposase] This site, attTn7, is specifically recognized by TnsD.
